<BlogLayout
  title="Case Study: Custom Winch Components for Offshore Sailing — 3D3D Blog"
  description="A real case study — designing, printing, and testing custom winch components for an offshore sailing campaign."
  datePublished="2026-03-05"
  author="Ken"
>
  <h2>The Problem</h2>

  <p>
    During boat prep for the Newport Bermuda campaign, we identified a problem with the primary sheet winches. The self-tailing jaws on both winches were worn. The teeth that grip the line had rounded off after years of use, and under load the line was slipping — releasing a few centimetres at a time under heavy wind. On a daysail, it's annoying. On an ocean race, it's a safety issue.
  </p>

  <p>
    Replacement self-tailing assemblies from the winch manufacturer were backordered for four months. The winches are an older model — still perfectly functional mechanically, but parts availability is drying up as the manufacturer pushes newer product lines. Buying new winches was out of budget. We needed another option.
  </p>

  <h2>The Design Process</h2>

  <p>
    I removed one of the self-tailing jaw assemblies and brought it to the shop. The first step was measuring every dimension — the mounting geometry, the tooth profile, the jaw spacing, the pivot points. I used digital calipers and a profile gauge to capture the tooth form, then modelled the entire assembly in Fusion 360.
  </p>

  <p>
    The original part was cast aluminum with a hardened steel jaw insert. Reproducing it in metal would have meant machining or casting — expensive and slow. Instead, I redesigned the jaw profile for 3D printing, optimizing the tooth geometry for the line diameter we run (10mm double-braid polyester) and adding material where the original design had fatigue-prone thin sections.
  </p>

  <p>
    The key design decisions:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Tooth profile:</strong> Sharper entry angle than the original to bite into the line braid more aggressively. Deeper grooves to channel water away from the grip surface</li>
    <li><strong>Material thickness:</strong> Added 2mm to the jaw walls where the original casting had shown cracking. FDM parts have different stress concentrations than castings — you design for the process</li>
    <li><strong>Mounting interface:</strong> Kept the original bolt pattern so the new jaws drop onto the existing winch drum without modification</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Material Selection</h2>

  <p>
    This was the critical decision. The jaws see constant salt spray, UV exposure, and high intermittent loads when a sheet is loaded in heavy wind. The line runs across the teeth under tension, so abrasion resistance matters.
  </p>

  <p>
    I tested three materials:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>PETG-CF:</strong> Good stiffness and easy to print, but the teeth showed visible wear after just a few hours of loaded testing. The carbon fibres actually made the abrasion worse — they polished smooth instead of maintaining grip</li>
    <li><strong>PA6-CF:</strong> Much better abrasion resistance. The nylon base is naturally slippery against most materials but grips braided line well due to the texture of the FDM layer lines. The carbon fibre added the stiffness needed to prevent flexing under load</li>
    <li><strong>PPA-CF:</strong> Best overall performance but overkill for the temperature requirements. The extra cost wasn't justified for this application</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    We went with PA6-CF. Specifically, Polymaker's PA6-CF, printed at 0.15mm layer height with 6 walls and 40% gyroid infill for maximum rigidity. Each jaw took about 4 hours to print.
  </p>

  <h2>Testing</h2>

  <p>
    I don't put untested parts on a boat that's going offshore. The testing sequence:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Bench test:</strong> Mounted the jaws on the winch and loaded the line to 50kg using a luggage scale and a cleat. The jaws gripped clean with zero slip. Repeated 200 times to simulate sheet-in, release, sheet-in cycles.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Salt soak:</strong> Submerged a test jaw in salt water for 72 hours, then repeated the load test. No change in performance or dimensions. PA6-CF doesn't absorb water as aggressively as unfilled nylon, and the salt didn't attack the surface.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>On-water test:</strong> Installed both jaws and sailed in 18-22 knot winds for an afternoon. Loaded the sheets hard, tacked repeatedly, simulated heavy-weather conditions. The jaws held. The line seated cleanly in the teeth every time.
  </p>

  <h2>The Result</h2>

  <p>
    Total cost for both winch jaw assemblies: approximately $35 in material and about 12 hours of design and print time. The OEM replacement parts, if they'd been available, would have been over $400 for the pair plus shipping from Europe.
  </p>

  <p>
    The printed jaws have been in service for six weeks as of this writing. No wear visible on the teeth, no cracking, no dimensional change. I printed two spare sets that live in the parts locker on board — if a jaw ever does fail, the replacement is already on the boat and can be swapped in ten minutes with a single wrench.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is what 3D printing does best. Not replacing mass-manufactured commodity parts — solving specific problems on specific equipment where the original supply chain has failed. The winches work better now than they did with the worn OEM jaws, at a tenth of the cost and in a fraction of the time.
  </p>
